Here’s what you need to embed a fully-working countdown into the “NODE_TIMER” section of your app.

1. Parameters from the Figma design  
   • Ele: vocab_timer_user001  
   • StartDate: 2025-07-15T09:00:00  
   • EndDate: 2025-08-15T09:30:00  
   • EndFunc: supply a callback as a **string** (e.g. "handleTimeUp")—the API rejects null.

2. Countdown initialisation snippet (React example)

```jsx
import { CountDown_StartAndEndDate } from 'your-sdk-path';

/* Optional callback executed when time is up */
function handleTimeUp () {
  alert('Time up!');
}

useEffect(() => {
  CountDown_StartAndEndDate({
    Ele: 'vocab_timer_user001',
    StartDate: '2025-07-15T09:00:00',
    EndDate: '2025-08-15T09:30:00',
    EndFunc: 'handleTimeUp'          // must be a non-empty string
  });
}, []);
```

3. Minimal HTML container (if you’re not in React)

```html
<div id="vocab_timer_user001"></div>
<script>
  function handleTimeUp() { alert('Time up!'); }

  CountDown_StartAndEndDate({
    Ele: 'vocab_timer_user001',
    StartDate: '2025-07-15T09:00:00',
    EndDate: '2025-08-15T09:30:00',
    EndFunc: 'handleTimeUp'
  });
</script>
```

4. What happens  
• Before 9 AM on 15 July 2025: “Countdown scheduled to start at 2025-07-15T09:00:00”.  
• Between the two dates: the remaining seconds are displayed and updated every second inside the element vocab_timer_user001.  
• After 9 : 30 AM on 15 Aug 2025: “Countdown already ended.” and `handleTimeUp()` fires.

Insert this snippet where the Figma-generated `<CountdownTimer …/>` placeholder currently sits, and the timer will operate exactly as specified in your design.

