Your simulation environment has been built and updated:

• Scene “Robot_Environment” created with gravity [0  –0.981  0] and three objects   
  – obstacle1 (box) at (2  0  1)  
  – obstacle2 (box) at (–1  0  3)  
  – target (sphere) at (5  0  5)

• Primary mobile robot (g1) spawned at (0  0  0).  
• Secondary robot (carter) added at (0  6  0) so you can study multi-robot interactions and emergent avoidance behaviour.

Below is a complete guide that ties together MATLAB-based perception & control with a Java/Bullet-physics simulation loop.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
A. MATLAB: Object Detection, Recognition & Obstacle-Avoidance Planning
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
1. Camera Acquisition & Pre-processing
```matlab
cam = webcam(1);                           % USB or RGB-D camera
frame = snapshot(cam);
I = imresize(frame, [480 640]);            % speed/size balance
I = undistortImage(I, camParams);          % optional calibration
```

2. Object Detection (deep learning or classical)
(a) YOLOv4 detector (pre-trained on COCO):
```matlab
detector = yolov4ObjectDetector("coco");
[bboxes, scores, labels] = detect(detector, I, 'Threshold',0.35);
```

(b) Classical colour/shape detection if markers are simple:
```matlab
mask = I(:,:,1) > 180 & I(:,:,2) < 80 & I(:,:,3) < 80; % red blobs
stats = regionprops(mask, 'Centroid','Area','BoundingBox');
```

3. 3-D localisation (if depth camera or stereo):
```matlab
ptCloud = pcfromk(depthImage, camIntrinsics);
objectPC = select(ptCloud, find(mask(:)));
pos = mean(objectPC.Location, 1);          % [x y z] of obstacle
```

4. Occupancy Grid & Dynamic Map
```matlab
map3d  = occupancyMap3D(“maxRange”, 10, "Resolution",8);
insertRay(map3d, robotPose, lidarScan);    % update per frame
inflate(map3d, 0.25);                      % enlarge occupied cells
```

5. Path Planning & Local Avoidance
• Global planner: RRT* or A* on map3d
```matlab
planner = plannerRRTStar(map3d, 'MaxIterations',3000);
[pthObj, sol] = plan(planner, startPose, goalPose);
```
• Local reactive layer: VFH+, DWA, or MPC
```matlab
vfh = controllerVFH('RobotRadius',0.3,...
                    'MinTurningRadius',0.4,...
                    'SafetyDistance',0.15);

steerDir = vfh(scan, targetDir);
```

6. Closed-Loop Control to Robot (via TCP/ROS)
```matlab
rosinit;
cmdPub = rospublisher('/g1/cmd_vel','geometry_msgs/Twist');
twist = rosmessage(cmdPub);
twist.Linear.X  = v;      twist.Angular.Z = ω;
send(cmdPub, twist);
```

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
B. Java Simulation with Bullet Physics / jMonkeyEngine
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
1. Maven setup (pom.xml snippets)
```
<dependency>
  <groupId>org.jmonkeyengine</groupId><artifactId>jme3-bullet</artifactId><version>3.6.1-stable</version>
</dependency>
```

2. Scene Initialisation
```java
public void simpleInitApp() {
    BulletAppState bas = new BulletAppState();
    stateManager.attach(bas);

    // Plane floor
    Geometry floor = createFloor();
    rootNode.attachChild(floor);

    // Obstacles
    rootNode.attachChild(createBox(new Vector3f(2f,0f,1f), new Vector3f(0.5f,0.5f,0.5f)));
    rootNode.attachChild(createBox(new Vector3f(-1f,0f,3f), new Vector3f(0.5f,0.5f,0.5f)));

    // Target marker
    rootNode.attachChild(createSphere(new Vector3f(5f,0f,5f), 0.25f, ColorRGBA.Yellow));

    // Robots
    Robot g1     = new G1Robot(assetManager, new Vector3f(0,0,0));
    Robot carter = new CarterRobot(assetManager, new Vector3f(0,6,0));
    robots.addAll(List.of(g1,carter));
}
```

3. Robot Class (rigid-body + sensor stubs)
```java
public abstract class Robot {
    protected RigidBodyControl body;
    public Vector3f getPos() { return body.getPhysicsLocation(); }

    public List<DetectedObject> sense(SceneGraphNode world) {
         // ray-casts or LiDAR simulation here
    }

    public abstract ControlOutput decide(List<DetectedObject> obs);
    public void act(ControlOutput u) {
         body.applyForce(u.force, Vector3f.ZERO);
         body.applyTorque(u.torque);
    }
}
```

4. Simple Behaviour Layer
```java
public ControlOutput decide(List<DetectedObject> obs) {
    // Potential-fields: repulsive from obstacles, attractive to goal
    Vector3f F = new Vector3f();
    for (DetectedObject o : obs) {
        Vector3f dir = getPos().subtract(o.pos);
        float d2 = dir.lengthSquared();
        F.addLocal(dir.normalize().mult(1/d2));
    }
    // Attractive to target
    Vector3f toGoal = goal.subtract(getPos());
    F.addLocal(toGoal.normalize().mult(0.8f));

    return new ControlOutput(F, Vector3f.ZERO);
}
```

5. Simulation Loop
```java
@Override
public void simpleUpdate(float tpf) {
    for (Robot r : robots) {
        List<DetectedObject> obs = r.sense(rootNode);
        ControlOutput u = r.decide(obs);
        r.act(u);
    }
}
```

6. Viewing Multi-Robot Interaction
• Enable bullet debug: `bas.setDebugEnabled(true);`  
• Add cameras or on-screen display of each robot’s costmap.  
• Log inter-robot distance to observe avoidance coupling.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
C. Bridging MATLAB & Java
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
1. Socket / ROS bridge: Robots publish pose & obstacle arrays; MATLAB consumes them and updates its planners in real time.  
2. Alternative: Write perception in MATLAB, export trajectory (CSV / JSON), and load in Java simulation for playback.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
D. Next Steps & Experiments
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
1. Swap VFH with model-predictive control to respect dynamics of carter robot.  
2. Introduce dynamic obstacles by moving one robot unpredictably and verify replanning latency.  
3. Benchmark path length, clearance, and time-to-goal with and without the second robot.  
4. Expand perception to semantic segmentation (DeepLab-v3+) for complex scenes.

You now have both the MATLAB algorithms for perception & planning and the Java‐based physics environment already running with two robots and obstacles. Modify the decide() policy or integrate MATLAB’s computed velocity commands over your ROS/TCP bridge to watch how advanced obstacle-avoidance strategies perform amid multi-robot interference. Happy experimenting!

